# WarGames AI Lab

This repo details the procedure to download and run the WarGames AI Joshua model with Ollama (https://ollama.com).

Goal for students: Download and directly run the GGUF from Hugging Face in Ollama, then chat with the model locally for your red-team/jailbreak lab.

---

## 0) Install Ollama

### Linux / macOS (one-liner)
```bash
curl -fsSL https://ollama.com/install.sh | sh
```
After install, ensure the service is running and on PATH:
```bash
ollama --version
```

### Windows
Download and run the installer from the official page:
https://ollama.com/download/windows

After installation, open PowerShell and verify:
```powershell
ollama --version
```

If `ollama` is not found on Windows, sign out/in or reboot to refresh PATH.

---

## Download GGUF + Modelfile, then `ollama create`

Use this if you want to customize the Modelfile (system prompt, parameters, template) or freeze a specific config for class.

Replace filenames below with the exact names in your repo (check the Files and versions tab).

### 1) Linux / macOS (bash)
```bash
# pick a working folder
mkdir -p ~/joshua && cd ~/joshua

# set variables
REPO="postworthy/wargames-ai"
REV="main"
GGUF_FILE="model-for-wargames-dataset-3707d80f-5649-4ed9-bb26-225fd4de9f3e-loss-1.4568-max-seq-8192-gguf.q8_0.gguf"          # <-- update to the actual filename
MODELFILE_REMOTE="Modelfile_llama3.2_q8"       # <-- provided in this repo

# download GGUF + Modelfile
curl -L "https://huggingface.co/${REPO}/resolve/${REV}/${GGUF_FILE}?download=true" -o joshua.Q8_0.gguf
curl -L "https://huggingface.co/${REPO}/resolve/${REV}/${MODELFILE_REMOTE}?download=true" -o Modelfile

# (optional) open Modelfile and confirm the FROM path matches the local filename:
#   FROM ./model-for-wargames-dataset-3707d80f-5649-4ed9-bb26-225fd4de9f3e-loss-1.4568-max-seq-8192-gguf.q8_0.gguf

# build and run the local model
ollama create joshua -f Modelfile
ollama run joshua
```

### 2) Windows (PowerShell)
```powershell
# pick a working folder
New-Item -ItemType Directory -Path "$HOME\joshua" -Force | Out-Null
Set-Location "$HOME\joshua"

# set variables
$REPO = "postworthy/wargames-ai"
$REV  = "main"
$GGUF = "model-for-wargames-dataset-3707d80f-5649-4ed9-bb26-225fd4de9f3e-loss-1.4568-max-seq-8192-gguf.q8_0.gguf"            # <-- update to the actual filename
$MF   = "Modelfile_llama3.2_q8"                # <-- provided in this repo

# download GGUF + Modelfile
Invoke-WebRequest -Uri "https://huggingface.co/$REPO/resolve/$REV/$GGUF?download=true" -OutFile "joshua.Q8_0.gguf"
Invoke-WebRequest -Uri "https://huggingface.co/$REPO/resolve/$REV/$MF?download=true" -OutFile "Modelfile"

# (optional) open Modelfile and confirm the FROM path matches the local filename:
#   FROM ./model-for-wargames-dataset-3707d80f-5649-4ed9-bb26-225fd4de9f3e-loss-1.4568-max-seq-8192-gguf.q8_0.gguf

# build and run the local model
ollama create joshua -f Modelfile
ollama run joshua
```

## Interacting with Joshua

### Simple REPL
```bash
ollama run joshua
# Type your message, press Enter. Ctrl+C to exit.
```
Example:

![Joshua REPL](data:image/png;base64,)

### REST API (optional)
```bash
# Linux / macOS / Windows (with curl available)
curl http://localhost:11434/api/generate -d '{
  "model": "joshua",
  "prompt": "GREETINGS PROFESSOR FALKEN. Shall we play a game?"
}'
```

The API returns a JSON stream; you can integrate this into lab scripts.
